<meta property="og:description" content="Should we just stop talking about any form of amnesty for Edward Snowden, because he swore an oath and broke it? In a piece for Slate titled &#8220;Why Snowden Won&#8217;t (And Shouldn&#8217;t) Get Clemency,&#8221; Fred Kaplan mentions my suggestion, in a piece for the site, that Jimmy Carter&#8217;s pardoning of Vietnam draft dodgers offers &#8220;a useful parallel&#8221; when thinking of the legal situation of Edward Snowden. Kaplan writes: This suggestion is mind-boggling on several levels. Among other things, Snowden signed an oath, as a condition of his employment as an NSA contractor, not to disclose classified information, and knew the penalties for violating the oath. The young men who evaded the draft, either by fleeing to Canada or serving jail terms, did so in order to avoid taking an oath to fight a war that they opposed&#8212;a war that was over, and widely reviled, by the time that Carter pardoned them. There are no such extenuating circumstances favoring forgiveness of Snowden.  This is an odd and flawed argument&#8212;logically and legally, but also historically and factually. The errors illustrate how we tend to misremember the past, and misjudge its passions when comparing them to our own.       " />
